==English==

===Etymology===
First attested 1555–1565;<ref name="D.C-etym">R:Dictionary.com 1.1</ref> from {{etyl|la}} {{term|colloquium||conversation|lang=la}},<ref name="D.C-etym"/><ref name="AHD-etym">{{R:American Heritage 2000}}</ref> from {{term|com-||together, with|lang=la}} (English {{term|com-|lang=en}}) + form of {{term|loquor||speak|lang=la}} (from which English {{term|locution|lang=en}} and other words).<ref>{{R:Online Etymology Dictionary}}</ref>

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK|US}} {{enPR|kŏl'ə-kwē}}, {{IPA|/ˈkɒl.ə.kwi/}}, {{SAMPA|/"kQl.e.kwi/}}
* {{audio|Colloquy pronunciation.ogg|Audio (US)}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|colloquies}}

# A formal [[conversation]].
# A formal [[conference]].
# A written [[discourse]].
# {{legal}} A discussion during a [[trial]] in which a judge ensures that the [[defendant]] understands what is taking place in the trial and what their rights are.

====Usage notes====
Note that while {{term|colloquial|lang=en}} refers specifically to ''informal'' conversation, '''colloquy''' and {{term|colloquium|lang=en}} refer instead to ''formal'' conversation.

